Secret of the Polyglot
----------------------------------------------------------------
Platform   : picoCTF 2024
Category   : Forensics
Difficulty : Easy
----------------------------------------------------------------

Objective
----------------------------------------------------------------
A suspicious file named flag.pdf was provided. The NOC reported
conflicting information about its true file type. The goal was
to examine the file, understand its dual nature, and extract all
hidden information to reconstruct the full flag.

Tools Used
----------------------------------------------------------------
- exiftool    : reads metadata and detects true file type
- binwalk     : scans files for embedded file signatures
- xxd         : displays raw hex bytes of a file
- python3     : used to carve out the PNG portion by byte offset
- pdftotext   : extracts readable text content from PDF files

Tools Learned
----------------------------------------------------------------
- A polyglot file is a single file that is simultaneously valid
  in two or more formats at the same time.
- binwalk reports byte offsets where each embedded file begins.
- xxd confirms true file structure by showing raw magic bytes.
- dd and Python can both carve files by byte offset. Python is
  more reliable when dd behaves unexpectedly.

Steps
----------------------------------------------------------------
1. Downloaded the suspicious file flag.pdf from the challenge.

2. Ran exiftool to inspect metadata:

      exiftool flag.pdf

   exiftool reported the true file type as PNG despite the .pdf
   extension. It also issued a warning:

      Warning: Trailer data after PNG IEND chunk

   This confirmed something was hidden after the PNG ended.

3. Ran binwalk to scan for all embedded file signatures:

      binwalk flag.pdf

   Output revealed two files inside:
   - PNG image at byte offset 0
   - PDF document at byte offset 914

4. Attempted extraction with binwalk:

      binwalk -e --run-as=root flag.pdf

   binwalk only extracted the zlib stream, not the PNG and PDF
   separately. Manual carving was needed.

5. Verified the true file structure using xxd:

      xxd flag.pdf | head -3

   First bytes confirmed: 8950 4e47 (the PNG magic signature).
   The file genuinely starts as a PNG.

6. Carved out the PNG portion using Python:

      python3 -c "
      data = open('flag.pdf','rb').read(914)
      open('clean.png','wb').write(data)
      "

   Verified with:

      file clean.png

   Output confirmed: PNG image data, 50x50, 8-bit/color RGBA.

7. Opened clean.png using eog:

      eog clean.png

   The image displayed the first half of the flag as visible text:

      picoCTF{f1u3n7_

8. Extracted the PDF portion using dd:

      dd if=flag.pdf of=extracted.pdf bs=1 skip=914

9. Extracted readable text from the PDF:

      pdftotext extracted.pdf -

   Output contained the second half of the flag:

      1n_pn9_&_pdf_249d05c0}

10. Combined both halves to form the complete flag.

Key Takeaway
----------------------------------------------------------------
Never trust a file extension. A file is what its bytes say it
is, not what its name claims. Polyglot files exploit the fact
that different programs read different parts of a file. Always
run exiftool and binwalk on any suspicious file in a forensics
challenge. When binwalk fails to extract cleanly, use the byte
offsets it reports to carve files manually with dd or Python.
The magic bytes at the start of a file (readable via xxd) are
the ground truth of what a file actually is.

Flag
----------------------------------------------------------------
picoCTF{f1u3n7_1n_pn9_&_pdf_249d05c0}
